🔷 CI/CD Pipeline Architecture Explanation

This project demonstrates a fully automated Continuous Integration and Continuous Deployment (CI/CD) pipeline. The pipeline ensures that whenever a developer pushes code, it is automatically built, tested, and deployed without manual intervention.

🔹 1. Developer (Code Creation)

The process starts with the developer writing code for a Java web application on their local machine.

The developer uses Git to manage source code.
Changes are committed and pushed to the remote repository.
🔹 2. GitHub Repository

GitHub acts as the central version control system.

Stores the application source code.
Maintains version history.
Allows collaboration among developers.

Whenever code is pushed to the main branch, it triggers the next stage automatically.

🔹 3. Webhook Trigger

A webhook is configured in GitHub.

It sends an HTTP request to Jenkins when changes occur.
This eliminates the need for manual triggering.

👉 This is the key component that enables automation.

🔹 4. Jenkins Server (CI/CD Engine)

Jenkins is the heart of the pipeline.

Once triggered, Jenkins performs the following tasks:

✔ Pull Code
Fetches the latest code from GitHub repository.
✔ Build Process
Uses Maven to compile the project.
✔ Package Application
Converts the project into a .war file (Web Application Archive).

👉 This stage ensures the code is ready for deployment.

🔹 5. Build Tool – Apache Maven

Maven is used inside Jenkins to:

Compile source code
Manage dependencies
Package the application

Command used:

clean package

Output:
👉 A .war file inside the target/ directory

🔹 6. Artifact (WAR File)

The generated .war file is the final build artifact.

Contains compiled code and resources
Ready to be deployed on a web server
🔹 7. SSH Deployment

Jenkins uses SSH to connect to the target server.

Securely transfers the .war file
Automates deployment process
Removes manual file upload
🔹 8. Application Server – Apache Tomcat

Apache Tomcat is used to deploy the application.

Receives the .war file
Automatically extracts and runs the application
Hosts the application on port 8080
🔹 9. Live Application (End Users)

After deployment:

The application becomes accessible via browser
Users can interact with the live system

Example:

http://<Tomcat-Public-IP>:8080/app-name
🔷 End-to-End Flow Summary
Developer pushes code to GitHub
GitHub webhook triggers Jenkins
Jenkins pulls latest code
Maven builds and packages .war file
Jenkins sends file via SSH
Tomcat deploys the application
Application becomes live
